# Angular forms — Signal Forms

All forms in `frontend/` use **Signal Forms** (`@angular/forms/signals`). Do **not** use `ReactiveFormsModule`, `FormGroup`, `FormControl`, `FormBuilder`, `ngModel`, or `FormsModule`.

## Pattern

```typescript
import { Component, signal } from '@angular/core';
import { form, FormField, required } from '@angular/forms/signals';

readonly model = signal( { name: '', email: '' } );

readonly form = form( this.model, ( schema ) => {
  required( schema.name );
  required( schema.email );
} );
```

```html
<form (submit)="onSubmit( $event )">
  <input type="text" [formField]="form.name" />
  <button type="submit" [disabled]="form().invalid()">Save</button>
</form>
```

## Rules

- Model = `signal(...)`; field tree = `form(model, schemaFn)`.
- Bind inputs with `[formField]` — import `FormField` in the component.
- Validators (`required`, `email`, `minLength`, …) live in the schema callback.
- Read state via signals: `form().invalid()`, `form.name().value()`, `form.name().touched()`.
- On submit: `event.preventDefault()`, then `form().markAsTouched()` (marks descendants too).
- Do **not** set `required` / `disabled` / `readonly` / `min` / `max` on the input manually — `[formField]` syncs them from the schema.
- Arrays: hold an array in the model signal + `applyEach`; mutate with `.update()`, not `FormArray`.
